    <p>
        <em> <alert>Goal:</alert> </em> To solve linear first-order differential equations with an integrating factor.
    </p>

    <p>
        <alert>Warm-up Exercise:</alert> Solve <m>\dfrac{dy}{dx}-3y=6</m>.
    </p>
    A first-order differential equation of the form is said to be a <alert>linear equation</alert> in the variable <m>y</m>.
    <p>
        By dividing both sides of the above equation by the leading coefficient <m>a_{1}(x)</m>, we obtain the <alert>standard form</alert> of a linear equation.
    </p>

    <p>
        The method of solution for this type of equation relies on the fact that the left-hand side can be recast into the form of the derivative of a product by multiplying both sides of the equation by a special function.
    </p>

    <p>
    </p>

    <p>
        The function <m>\mu(x)=e^{\int P(x) dx}</m> is called an <em> </em> for the linear equation in standard form.
    </p>
    <alert>Steps for Solving a Linear First-Order Equation</alert>
    <ol>
        <li>
            <p>
                Put the linear equation in standard form.
            </p>
        </li>

        <li>
            <p>
                Identify <m>P(x)</m> and then find the integrating factor <m>e^{\int P(x) dx}</m>.
                (No constant needs to be used in evaluating the indefinite integral <m>\int P(x) dx</m>.)
            </p>
        </li>

        <li>
            <p>
                Multiply both sides of the standard form equation by the integrating factor.
                The left-hand side of the resulting equation is automatically the derivative of the product of the integrating factor <m>e^{\int P(x) dx}</m> and <m>y</m>:
            </p>
        </li>

        <li>
            <p>
                Integrate both sides of the resulting equation and solve for <m>y</m>.
            </p>
        </li>
    </ol>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                One Solve <m>\dfrac{dy}{dx}-3y=6</m>.
